{"title_page": "Belgrade City Museum", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Belgrade City Museum\n| native_name         = \u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\n| native_name_lang    = sr\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{Coord|44.804198|N|20.461199|E|type:landmark_region:SR|display=inline, title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date and age|1903}}\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Belgrade]], Serbia\n| type                = \n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = Jelena Medakovi\u0107\n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.mgb.org.rs/}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\nThe '''Belgrade City Museum''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430}}) is a museum located in [[Belgrade]], Serbia. Founded in 1903, the museum operates with several cultural institutions: [[Museum of Ivo Andri\u0107|Ivo Andri\u0107 Museum]], [[Princess Ljubica's Residence]], [[Museum of Paja Jovanovi\u0107|Paja Jovanovi\u0107 Museum]], Banjica Concentration Camp Museum, Collection of Icons Sekuli\u0107, [[Vin\u010da-Belo Brdo|Archaeological Site Vin\u010da]] and Jovan Cviji\u0107 Museum.\n\nThe Belgrade City Museum contains over 2,500 paintings, graphics, [[Watercolor painting|aquarelle]]s and drawings. It contains numerous paintings by Serbian painters [[Paja Jovanovi\u0107]], [[Sava \u0160umanovi\u0107]], [[Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107]], [[Nade\u017eda Petrovi\u0107]], [[Petar Lubarda]] and others. Among others, it contains paintings and graphics by foreign artists [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], [[Mikl\u00f3s Barab\u00e1s]] and [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot]].\n\n== Collections ==\n[[File:Kosovo Maiden, Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107, 1919.jpg|right|thumb|''Kosovo Maiden'', by [[Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107]]]]\nThe Belgrade City Museum collections are:\n* Prehistory\n* Antique\n* Middle Ages\n* Coins and Medals\n* Arheogical site Vinca\n* History of Belgrade 1521-1941\n* History of Belgrade since 1941\n* Fine Arts and Music before 1950\n* Fine Arts and Music after 1950\n* Applied Arts and Ethnology\n* Education and Science\n* Culture and Literature\n* Urban Planning and Architecture\n\nThe museum also operates an outpost in, and documenting, the former [[Banjica concentration camp]].\n\n== New building ==\n[[File:\u041a\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430 7- \u043f\u0443\u043a\u0430 2012-09-28 16-24-14.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Barracks of the 7th Regiment, where the museum will be relocated]]\n\nCity awarded the former military building in the Resavska Street, and the adjoining lot, for the future location of the Belgrade City Museum.<ref name=Politika>{{cite news | author = Sla\u0111ana Raner | title = \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u045b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0443\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Belgrade will get a museum it deserves | newspaper = [[Politika]]-Moja ku\u0107a | page = 2 | language = Serbian | date = 24 August 2018}}</ref> The representative edifice was built in 1899 after the design of {{ill|Dragutin \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107|sr|\u0414\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0402\u043e\u0440\u0452\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b (\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430)}}. Originally, it served as the military barrack. Built during the rule of [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander Obrenovi\u0107]], the building considered one of the most beautiful in Belgrade at the time, and hosted the elite guards unit. It was \"the pride of the throne\" and was meant to celebrate the power of the Serbian army and its loyalty to the dynasty. However, it was the guards unit from this very barrack which conducted the [[May Coup (Serbia)|May Coup]] in 1903 when the Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty was dethroned and King Alexander and [[Queen Draga]] were executed.<ref name=Politika1>{{cite news | author = Nenad Novak Stefanovi\u0107 | title = \u0408\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u0435 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0430 - \u0412\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0443 \u0412\u043e\u0458\u043d\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0443 | trans-title = One house one story - Chivalry style in Military Quarter | newspaper = Politika-Moja ku\u0107a | page = 1 | language = Serbian | date = 7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe building was located in the Military Quarter of Belgrade, which stretched between the streets of [[Kneza Milo\u0161a Street|Kneza Milo\u0161a]], Kralja Milana, Bir\u010daninova and the [[Slavija Square]]. The quarter included the buildings of the [[Serbian General Staff]], Military Academy, Officers Storehouse, Officers House and the [[Manje\u017e|Royal Cavalry Guard training ground]]. In terms of architecture, \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 implemented the style of the German [[Ritter]] barracks. Hence, above the entry nigh arch of the cart gate there are two square-shaped towers. The entire entry section is indented, leaving a small ''piazetta'' where the [[Muster (military)|musters]] can be organized. The fa\u00e7ade is ornamented with the sculptures symbolizing knights in armours or [[coats of arms]]. During the [[Interbellum]], the 7th Regiment was situated in it. In 1927 Ministry of the Army decided to upgrade the edifice by adding the third floor. They hired architect Bla\u017eo Vuki\u0107evi\u0107 Sarap, even though the original designer \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 was still alive.<ref name=Politika1/>\n\nIn 2018 the first phase of the complete reconstruction of the building was announced, before the museum can move in. Part of the building will be preserved while other parts will be upgraded and modernized. The inner yard will be restored and the exhibition rooms, depot, conservation area, library, work shops, archaeological [[lapidarium]] and amphitheater will be formed.<ref name=Politika/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[National Museum of Serbia]]\n* [[Beli Dvor|White Palace]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.mgb.org.rs/en}}\n* [http://www.arte.rs/en/ustanove/muzeji/muzej_grada_beograda-227/ Belgrade City Museum presentation at www.arte.rs]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{List of museums in Belgrade}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Museum Of The City Of Belgrade}}\n[[Category:Museums in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1903]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Savski Venac]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Belgrade City Museum\n| native_name         = \u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\n| native_name_lang    = sr\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{Coord|44.804198|N|20.461199|E|type:landmark_region:SR|display=inline, title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date and age|1903}}\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Belgrade]], Serbia\n| type                = \n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = Jelena Medakovi\u0107\n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.mgb.org.rs/}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\nThe '''Belgrade City Museum''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430}}) is a museum located in [[Belgrade]], Serbia. Founded in 1903, the museum operates with several cultural institutions: [[Museum of Ivo Andri\u0107|Ivo Andri\u0107 Museum]], [[Princess Ljubica's Residence]], [[Museum of Paja Jovanovi\u0107|Paja Jovanovi\u0107 Museum]], Banjica Concentration Camp Museum, Collection of Icons Sekuli\u0107, [[Vin\u010da-Belo Brdo|Archaeological Site Vin\u010da]] and Jovan Cviji\u0107 Museum.\n\nThe Belgrade City Museum contains over 2,500 paintings, graphics, [[Watercolor painting|aquarelle]]s and drawings. It contains numerous paintings by Serbian painters [[Paja Jovanovi\u0107]], [[Sava \u0160umanovi\u0107]], [[Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107]], [[Nade\u017eda Petrovi\u0107]], [[Petar Lubarda]] and others. Among others, it contains paintings and graphics by foreign artists [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], [[Mikl\u00f3s Barab\u00e1s]] and [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot]].\n\n== Collections ==\n[[File:Kosovo Maiden, Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107, 1919.jpg|right|thumb|''Kosovo Maiden'', by [[Uro\u0161 Predi\u0107]]]]\nThe Belgrade City Museum collections are:\n* Prehistory\n* Antique\n* Middle Ages\n* Coins and Medals\n* Arheogical site Vinca\n* History of Belgrade 1521-1941\n* History of Belgrade since 1941\n* Fine Arts and Music before 1950\n* Fine Arts and Music after 1950\n* Applied Arts and Ethnology\n* Education and Science\n* Culture and Literature\n* Urban Planning and Architecture\n\nThe museum also operates an outpost in, and documenting, the former [[Banjica concentration camp]].\n\n== New building ==\n[[File:\u041a\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430 7- \u043f\u0443\u043a\u0430 2012-09-28 16-24-14.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Barracks of the 7th Regiment, where the museum will be relocated]]\n\nCity awarded the former military building in the Resavska Street, and the adjoining lot, for the future location of the Belgrade City Museum.<ref name=Politika>{{cite news | author = Sla\u0111ana Raner | title = \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u045b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0443\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Belgrade will get a museum it deserves | newspaper = [[Politika]]-Moja ku\u0107a | page = 2 | language = Serbian | date = 24 August 2018}}</ref> The representative edifice was built in 1899 after the design of {{ill|Dragutin \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107|sr|\u0414\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0402\u043e\u0440\u0452\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b (\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430)}}. Originally, it served as the military barrack. Built during the rule of [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander Obrenovi\u0107]], the building considered one of the most beautiful in Belgrade at the time, and hosted the elite guards unit. It was \"the pride of the throne\" and was meant to celebrate the power of the Serbian army and its loyalty to the dynasty. However, it was the guards unit from this very barrack which conducted the [[May Coup (Serbia)|May Coup]] in 1903 when the Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty was dethroned and King Alexander and [[Queen Draga]] were executed.<ref name=Politika1>{{cite news | author = Nenad Novak Stefanovi\u0107 | title = \u0408\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u0435 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0430 - \u0412\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0443 \u0412\u043e\u0458\u043d\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0443 | trans-title = One house one story - Chivalry style in Military Quarter | newspaper = Politika-Moja ku\u0107a | page = 1 | language = Serbian | date = 7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe building was located in the Military Quarter of Belgrade, which stretched between the streets of [[Kneza Milo\u0161a Street|Kneza Milo\u0161a]], Kralja Milana, Bir\u010daninova and the [[Slavija Square]]. The quarter included the buildings of the [[Serbian General Staff]], Military Academy, Officers Storehouse, Officers House and the [[Manje\u017e|Royal Cavalry Guard training ground]]. In terms of architecture, \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 implemented the style of the German [[Ritter]] barracks. Hence, above the entry nigh arch of the cart gate there are two square-shaped towers. The entire entry section is indented, leaving a small ''piazetta'' where the [[Muster (military)|musters]] can be organized. The fa\u00e7ade is ornamented with the sculptures symbolizing knights in armours or [[coats of arms]]. During the [[Interbellum]], the 7th Regiment was situated in it. In 1927 Ministry of the Army decided to upgrade the edifice by adding the third floor. They hired architect Bla\u017eo Vuki\u0107evi\u0107 Sarap, even though the original designer \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 was still alive.<ref name=Politika1/>\n\nIn 2018 the first phase of the complete reconstruction of the building was announced, before the museum can move in. Part of the building will be preserved while other parts will be upgraded and modernized. The inner yard will be restored and the exhibition rooms, depot, conservation area, library, work shops, archaeological [[lapidarium]] and amphitheater will be formed.<ref name=Politika/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[National Museum of Serbia]]\n* [[Beli Dvor|White Palace]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.mgb.org.rs/en}}\n* [http://www.arte.rs/en/ustanove/muzeji/muzej_grada_beograda-227/ Belgrade City Museum presentation at www.arte.rs]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{List of museums in Belgrade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Museum Of The City Of Belgrade}}\n[[Category:Museums in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1903]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Savski Venac]]\n\n{{Serbia-struct-stub}}\n{{Europe-art-display-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belgrade_City_Museum"}
